videoData.title: A swarm of mini drones makes ... magic!
videoData.socialTitle: A swarm of mini drones makes ... magic!

nodes.whoTheyAre: Using technology and an array of special effects, Marco Tempest develops immersive environments that allow viewers to viscerally experience the magic of technology.
nodes.whyListen:
Marco Tempest began his performing career as a stage magician and manipulator, winning awards and establishing an international reputation as a master illusionist. His interest in computer-generated imagery led him to incorporate video and digital technology in his work -- and eventually to develop a new form of contemporary illusion. 

Tempest is the executive director of the NYC Magic Lab, a science consortium exploring illusion and digital technology. He is deeply embedded in the tech industry and has regular interactions with product teams in an advisory capacity and as a consultant or developer for prototype consumer technologies. He is a Director's Fellow at the MIT Media Lab and a creative consultant at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory.

videoData.description: Leading a swarm of small, buzzing flying machines, techno-magician Marco Tempest orchestrates a "cyber illusion" that will have you asking yourself: Was that science or magic?

cues.text:
So, I have a background
in technology and magic.

Their illusions accomplish
what technology cannot.

But what happens when
the technology of the day
What happens when you can do this?

that would have been
the magic of levitation.
Is it possible to create illusions

in a world where technology
makes anything possible?
Now, if you know how the trick is done,

But still, our imagination
is more powerful than our reasoning,

and it's easy to attribute
personality to machines.

But they are more than
mechanical flying machines.
They analyze the environment around them
and react to everything I do.

At once, algorithms allow these autonomous
machines to fly in close formation,

mathematics that can
be mistaken for intelligence,
to become an intelligent flying robot,
a machine that appears to be alive.

(Music plays 
"Close Encounters of the Third Kind")
OK, guys, time to go home.

There you go, a little bit to the left,
a little bit to the right.
